1. **Initialize a counter** to keep track of the number of oil deposits.
2. **Iterate through each cell** in the grid.
3. **When you encounter an oil pocket ('@')**, it indicates the start of a new oil deposit. Increment the counter and perform a DFS to mark all connected oil pockets as visited.
4. **During the DFS**, change the oil pockets ('@') to a different character (e.g., '*') to avoid counting them again.
5. Continue this process until all cells are processed.

Here's the complete Java function implementing this approach:

```java
public class OilDeposits {
    public static int countOilDeposits(char[][] grid) {
        if (grid == null || grid.length == 0 || grid[0].length == 0) {
            return 0;
        }

        int rows = grid.length;
        int cols = grid[0].length;
        int depositCount = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
                if (grid[i][j] == '@') {
                    depositCount++;
                    dfs(grid, i, j);
                }
            }
        }

        return depositCount;
    }

    private static void dfs(char[][] grid, int row, int col) {
        int rows = grid.length;
        int cols = grid[0].length;

        // Check for out of bounds or if the cell is not an oil pocket
        if (row < 0 || row >= rows || col < 0 || col >= cols || grid[row][col] != '@') {
            return;
        }

        // Mark the cell as visited by changing it to '*'
        grid[row][col] = '*';

        // Visit all four possible directions (up, down, left, right)
        dfs(grid, row - 1, col);
        dfs(grid, row + 1, col);
        dfs(grid, row, col - 1);
        dfs(grid, row, col + 1);
    }

